2x^2 + 6x + 10x + 30 &< 3x^2 + 24x + 9x + 72 \\
2x^2 + 16x + 30 &< 3x^2 + 33x + 72
\end{align*}
Subtracting $(2x^2 + 16x + 30)$ from both sides, we get:
\begin{align*}
0 &< x^2 + 17x + 42
\end{align*}
Now, we factor the quadratic trinomial:
\begin{align*}
0 &< (x + 6)(x + 7)
\end{align*}

Since both factors have positive coefficients, the signs of the factors will be the same. Thus, $x > -6$ and $x > -7$. The $x$ must be positive. Therefore, $x$ must be greater than $-6$.</think>
